I have developed and supported consumer applications for retail, hospitality (resorts), and healthcare industries.

When working on an application used by millions of users, you need solid strategies to ensure your customers are well-supported and satisfied.

Supporting millions of users effectively without building an enormous support team requires strategic thinking.

Here’s how I’ve approached this challenge across multiple products—and how you can too:


1. Identify user touchpoints

Start by mapping out all the touchpoints where users might seek help—front desk interactions, phone support lines, chatbots, and app store reviews.

Understand the types of questions and issues that arise at each touchpoint.

2. Empower your frontline teams

Equip your frontline teams—whether at the front desk, in marketing, or in customer support—with the right training and educational materials.

A user guide and a document listing frequently asked questions are invaluable resources for this group.

This enables them to resolve as many inquiries as possible at the first point of contact, reducing the need for escalations.


3. Establish a tiered support system

Create clear escalation processes so that issues that can't be resolved at the frontline are efficiently routed to the appropriate technical support or subject matter expert teams.

The goal is to address as much as possible at each level before involving analysts or developers.

4. Analyze and optimize continuously

Regularly analyze tickets, inquiries, and feedback to spot common trends.
Use this data to identify and prioritize issues that affect a large number of users.

Sometimes, simple changes like adjusting the layout, adding tooltips, or simplifying screen flows can resolve complex issues for many users.

5. Prioritize developer time for high-impact solutions

Focus on resolving problems that impact a large number of users.

Don’t get bogged down with individual cases—target the issues that will deliver the most significant overall benefit.

The key to effectively scaling support is empowering your frontline teams while reserving developer resources for the most impactful improvements.

This tiered approach ensures efficiency and enhances the user experience.

This is our team picture when I was in Dallas.

I was an on-site coordinator, managing an offshore team of 60 developers.

My role?

I gather requirements directly from the client, communicate them to my offshore team and validate the team's work with the client.

One day, a seemingly small issue turned into a major concern.

The client raised a bug about the tab order in the application.

But my offshore team argued it wasn’t a bug—it wasn’t specified in the initial requirements. They suggested handling it as a change request instead.

This situation is all too common in product development.

Business stakeholders and developers often make assumptions based on their perspectives.

The result?

Misalignment and an application that doesn’t fully meet expectations due to unspoken or implicit requirements.

Implicit requirements are those assumptions everyone makes but no one explicitly confirms.

Implicit requirements are those assumptions everyone makes but no one explicitly confirms.

Here’s a simple explanation:

Explicit requirements are the clearly defined needs of a product, while implicit requirements are the hidden or assumed expectations not explicitly stated during the requirements gathering process.

A great example comes from a study by Emebo Onyeka Chibueze.

He describes a scenario where a web application was developed for a publishing company.

The explicit requirements were clear—publishers could create, approve, and publish articles, and users could search for published content.

However, there was an implicit requirement that only published articles should appear in search results. This was never captured, leading to end-user frustration.

That Dallas incident was a turning point in how I approach product development.

I realized the need to identify potential gaps that could cause problems later.

I realized the need to identify potential gaps that could cause problems later. Ensuring developers build exactly what clients and stakeholders want became my priority.

This led me to deeply explore implicit requirements and how to manage them effectively.

So, how do you handle implicit requirements?

One effective strategy is creating an implicit requirements checklist to use during requirement-gathering sessions.

This checklist can help you uncover potential issues and align expectations early on, reducing the need for rework later.

If you're interested, I’d be happy to share a copy of the checklist I use.

Another strategy would be to create a list of standard assumptions you are making and share them with your client.

This list will help them think critically and ask follow-up questions, bringing everyone onto the same page.

The situation in Dallas profoundly impacted how I interact with clients, stakeholders, and developers.

Unclear and conflicting priorities can disrupt your timeline and cause product delays.

If you want to do everything at once, you won’t be able to do anything. Instead, focus on the most critical items and add everything else in the backlog to consider later. 

There are many prioritization frameworks available to help you.

Pick one of the frameworks, define your criteria, and score and rank all the items.

Let’s dive in,


1. MoSCoW Method

The MoSCoW method helps you categorize tasks into Must Have, Should Have, Could Have, and Won’t Have. 

This framework is crucial because it ensures you focus on the most critical features first. To use this method, list all your tasks and classify them into these four categories to prioritize essential features and address less critical ones later.

2. RICE Scoring Model

The RICE model evaluates tasks based on Reach, Impact, Confidence, and Effort. 

(Reach * Impact * Confidence) / Effort = RICE Score

List all the features and assign scores to each criterion, then calculate the RICE score to rank them. This method is effective because it quantifies the potential value (impact) and effort required for each feature. 


3. Kano Model

The Kano model differentiates between basic features, performance features, and delighters. 

Researcher Noraki Kano developed it to help product managers prioritize features and updates based on customer needs. This framework is important because it helps you understand what features will meet basic user needs and which ones will exceed expectations.

4. Value vs. Effort Matrix

The Value vs. Effort Matrix helps you plot features on a 2x2 grid based on their value and the effort required. 

This visualization makes it easy to identify high-value, low-effort items. Plot each feature on the matrix and focus on those in the high-value, low-effort quadrant. This ensures that you’re investing your resources in the most efficient way possible.


5. Weighted Scoring

Weighted Scoring involves assigning weights to different criteria based on their importance and scoring each feature accordingly. 

Define your criteria, assign weights, and score each feature to prioritize those that score the highest.

6. Cost of Delay

The cost of Delay evaluates the economic impact of delaying each feature. 

This approach helps you prioritize features that, if delayed, would result in significant financial loss. Calculate the cost of delay for each feature and prioritize those with the highest cost to minimize financial impact.


7. Opportunity Scoring

Opportunity Scoring focuses on identifying opportunities based on customer needs and the difficulty of meeting those needs. 

By following these frameworks, you’ll be well on your way to effective prioritization in product development. 

Work on the highest priority items and avoid spending efforts on less important work. 

This will help you stay focused, avoid unnecessary work, and ensure timely product launches.

Step 1: Define vision and goals

To achieve a clear vision and set meaningful goals:

• Identify the core problem your product solves. Start by understanding the pain points your product addresses.
• Ensure your goals are Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, and Time-bound (SMART).
• Make sure your vision is customer-centric and focuses on delivering value.

Start here, then move on to Step 2.

Step 2: Prioritize features and milestones

At this stage/step, you have two options:

• Option 1 - Categorize features based on their importance and impact on the core functionality. This involves identifying your Must-Have vs. Nice-to-Have.
• Option 2 - Use customer insights to prioritize features that deliver the most value.

There's no wrong answer, but you must decide what is more important.

Step 3: Develop the timeline

Focus on two core pillars:

Create a roadmap and timeline

• Divide the big features into smaller development tasks.
• Use t-shirt size to estimate each task and build a timeline.
• Set key milestones to track progress and celebrate small wins.

Once you master this, focus on:

Resource Allocation

• Ensure your team has the right skills and availability for each task.
• Assign the right people and tools to critical tasks.
• Regularly check if resources are being used efficiently.

Step 4: Review and adjust regularly

A common mistake most people make in this step is not adjusting the plan with the changes.

To avoid this, regularly:

• Schedule daily 15-minute check-ins to assess progress and identify any roadblocks.
• Arrange bi-weekly product demos and get early feedback from stakeholders.
• Adjust your plan based on new information.

By doing this, you ensure your project stays on track.

This final step is to ensure the product not only launches but also thrives post-launch:

• Identify all the non-technical activities needed before and after the launch.
• Identify who will handle communication, operation and promotional activities.
• Plan for customer support and maintenance. How will the team balance between bug fixes and new feature development?

A Financial Roadmap for Early-Stage Tech Startup Founders

As a founder, your goal is to transform your Idea into a startup through product development, adoption, scale and growth.

Building and growing a startup requires juggling many areas, such as product development, marketing, sales, team building, operations, legal, accounting, and finance. 

But, there's a key factor without which your startup might never succeed: finance. 

Without financial support, your idea may remain just a dream. 

This is why it's important for you to know everything about the key financial and investment stages a tech startup goes through.

Here’s a simplified guide to help you understand

The first stage: The first or pre-seed stage is to validate your idea and build a prototype with an investment range of up to $500,000, typically from personal savings, borrowing from friends and family, angel investors, grants, accelerators, and incubators.


The seed stage focuses on MVP development and gaining initial traction with an investment range of $500,000 to $2 million, usually from angel investors, seed funds, and early-stage venture capital. 


The Series A stage aims to scale your product and expand your market presence with an investment range of $2 million to $15 million, often from venture capital firms and corporate venture capital.

The Series B stage is for expanding operations and increasing market share. It typically involves investments of $15 million to $50 million from venture capital firms, private equity, and corporate venture capital.


The Series C stage and beyond are for achieving market dominance and further scaling with an investment range of $50 million and above, usually from venture capital firms, private equity firms, and strategic investors.


The growth stage involves aggressive expansion and optimizing efficiency with a variable investment range, often in the hundreds of millions, typically from private equity firms, late-stage venture capital, and institutional investors.


The mezzanine financing stage provides pre-IPO growth capital with multi-million-dollar investments, usually from mezzanine finance companies, venture capital firms, and private equity firms.

The IPO stage is for raising substantial public capital with investments in the hundreds of millions to billions of dollars from public and institutional investors.


The post-IPO stage focuses on continued growth and market expansion with highly variable investment amounts sourced from public and institutional investors.

Your journey is unique, but understanding these investment stages can help you be more strategic in growing your startup idea.

Each funding round propels you to the next level, providing financial support and aligning you with investors who believe in your vision and can help you reach new heights.

3. Three-point estimation: Estimate considering the best and worst cases, then use the average.

4. Expert judgment: get insight from senior developers, team leaders and project managers while estimating for projects.

5. Analogous estimation: We looked at the data from similar projects.

There are two methods of career planning. 

💥 1st - Backward Planning (Architect Mindset)

In this method, you first set a significant, ultimate goal and then trace a reverse journey back to the present. 

You decide where you want to be in 3 years. (or in a single year)

Then, you research everything you will need to do to get there. Break them into smaller goals and arrange them in a sequence over three years. You will get a three-year roadmap with milestones.

Finally, reverse-engineer your daily, weekly, and quarterly tasks based on this 3-year roadmap.

Just like an architect who creates a blueprint of a building, road, or bridge before building them.

Just like an architect who creates a blueprint of a building, road, or bridge before building them.

For example, to become a senior cloud solution architect in 3 years (a very specific outcome), you will have to learn a bunch of languages, frameworks, DevOps, and cloud technologies and do many projects.

I used this method twice.

When I was not able to find any job after college, I set my first long-term career goal of getting a job in one of the highly reputed companies within the next five years. I joined the 5th largest software development company in India within three years of setting that goal.

Then, I set a career goal of becoming a manager and achieved it.

Then, I set a career goal of becoming a manager and achieved it.


💥 2nd - Forward Planning (Gardening Mindset)

In this method, you identify a bunch of activities and create a roadmap with small, actionable goals leading to larger objectives. 

It is the idea of starting small and gradually building up to bigger goals.

There is unclarity about precisely what you will achieve and when. 

For example, a daily 60-minute exercise can lead you to a remarkable transformation. Your primary focus is to do it and fine-tune it as you make progress consistently.

Like a gardener, you support some branches and prune others.

I have been using this approach to build my coaching side hustle for the last two years. It has been one of the most exciting journeys so far.

💥 Which approach is better?

1st approach allows you to fine-tune your direction as you go. It can lead you to unimaginable outcomes.

In 2nd approach, the clarity of your destination can provide you with the exact steps to take over a longer duration.


💥 Which one do I use?

I use a combination of the two methods. I use 2nd approach to set my direction without picking a very specific goal.

Then, I set very specific quarterly goals. My long-term direction and the outcome of the previous quarter influence these goals.

It has resulted in outcomes I did not imagine two years ago.
